item.title: Carmen Weinstein
item.dc:creator: kh1242
item.content:encoded: This undated photograph shows Carmen Weinstein, leader of Egypts dwindling and aging Jewish community, with her dog. Weinstein died Saturday, April 13, 2013 at the age of 82, after leaving behind a legacy of preservation effort in preserving what is left of synagogues and a once-sprawling Jewish cemetery. Weinstein will be buried on Thursday in the Bassatine cemetery she worked tirelessly to save. According to a friend of Weinstein, Magda Haroun, only around 40 Egyptian Jews remain in the country, split between Cairo and the Mediterranean city of Alexandria that was also once a thriving multicultural and cosmopolitan hub.(AP Photo/Samir W Raafat) NO SALES

item.title: Mexico's Zapatista National Liberation A
item.dc:creator: kh1242
item.content:encoded: LA HORMIGA, MEXICO: Mexico's Zapatista National Liberation Army leader (EZLN) "Subcomandante Marcos" (R) delivers a speech beside of a local religious leader during a meeting with settlers from Oventic, Chamula and different surrounding areas 04 January, 2006 at La Hormiga settlement, San Cristobal de las Casas, Chiapas, Mexico. Former rebel Marcos has launched a national tour aimed at rallying support against globalization, just as Mexico's presidential campaign readies to go into high gear. AFP PHOTO/Susana GONZALEZ (Photo credit should read SUSANA GONZALEZ/AFP/Getty Images)
item.excerpt:encoded: At a rally launching the Zapatistas' Other Campaign in 2006, Subcomandante Marcos (right) describes the aid given to the rebels by Domingo Lopez Angel (Siddi Omar) (left) and the other indigenous residents of San Cristobal de las Casas. SUSANA GONZALEZ/AFP/Getty Images.
